{
  "doc_id": "48986",
  "text": "Increased global protein oxidation, as measured by protein carbonyls, was evident in the dermis of aged skin and in fibroblasts cultured in fragmented collagen. An age-dependent increase of protein carbonyl content has been reported in other human tissues, including brain and eye lens. [CITATION_1] 74 These data suggest that increased protein oxidation is a general feature of human aging that is not restricted to specific organs.",
